# NestJS Conventions

## Module structure
- One module per feature (e.g., `ScenarioModule`, `MetricsModule`)
- Feature folder: `src/<feature>/<feature>.module.ts`, `.controller.ts`, `.service.ts`
- DTOs live in `src/<feature>/dto/`

## Controllers
- Controllers are THIN — no business logic, no direct DB calls
- Only: receive request → call service → return result
- Use `@Body()`, `@Param()`, `@Query()` decorators
- Always apply `ParseIntPipe` / `DefaultValuePipe` for numeric query params

## Services
- Services own ALL business logic
- Services call: Prisma, MetricsService, getLogger()
- Async methods return typed Promises
- Use `try/catch` for error handling; update run status on failure

## DTOs
```typescript
// Always use class-validator decorators
export class CreateScenarioDto {
  @IsEnum(ScenarioType)
  type: ScenarioType;

  @IsOptional()
  @IsString()
  @MaxLength(120)
  name?: string;
}
```

## Dependency Injection
- Always inject via constructor
- Use `@InjectMetric('metric_name')` for Prometheus metrics
- Use `@Global()` for PrismaModule so it's available everywhere

## Error handling
- Use NestJS built-in exceptions: `NotFoundException`, `BadRequestException`
- Sentry captures go in service layer, not controllers
- Always log errors with `getLogger().error(message, { context })`

## Health checks
- `GET /health` must always return 200 when DB is reachable
- Use `@nestjs/terminus` for health indicators
